<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911021-0069</DOCNO><DOCID>911021-0069.</DOCID><HL>   Boeing Wins Jobs   From China, Poland   Totaling $750 Million</HL><DATE>10/21/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3</SO><CO>   BA</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AIRLINES (AIR)AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><RE>CHINA (CH)EASTERN EUROPE (EEU)EUROPE (EU)FAR EAST (FE)NORTH AMERICA (NME)POLAND (PL)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)WASHINGTON (WA)</RE><LP>   SEATTLE -- Boeing Co. said two customers bought 22 of its737 jetliners for a total of about $750 million.   In the larger deal, Boeing said the Chinese governmentconverted 13 options for 737-300s into firm orders in atransaction valued at about $450 million. The exercise of theoptions, which were taken in May 1990, marks the thirdcontract the Chinese have signed this year with Boeing.</LP><TEXT>   Boeing also said LOT Polish Airlines placed nine ordersfor 737 jets in a transaction valued at about $300 million.LOT also took options for two more planes. Of the nineorders, four are 737-400s and five are 737-500s.   Last month, McDonnell Douglas Corp. called for aninvestigation by the Polish government into LOT's decision tocast aside an agreement to buy nine of its MD80 jetliners andswitch to Boeing aircraft. McDonnell Douglas said it didn'tknow what has happened to its request. &quot;We're hopeful thatthe Polish government will look into the matter,&quot; a spokesmansaid.   Boeing said the LOT order, its first with the airline,will make LOT the largest operator of Boeing aircraft inEastern Europe.</TEXT></DOC>